    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1989-04-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1989-04-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="11"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d11">
                <head>11. Record of Decisions of an Arms Control Policy Coordinating Committee
                        Meeting<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d11fn1">Source: <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGHW_1">George H.W. Bush</persName> Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGHW_1">Bush</persName> Presidential Records, National
                        Security Council, <persName corresp="#p_DRA_1">Richard A. Davis</persName>
                        Files, Subject Files, OA/ID CF01590–009, Arms Control PCC [2].
                        Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1989-04-05">April 5, 1989</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The following were agreed to:</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">
                    <gloss target="#t_CW_1">CW</gloss> Bilaterals with the Soviets</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>A decision on resumption is required before Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJA_1">Baker</persName> meets with Foreign Minister
                            <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Shevardnadze</persName> in May. No decision
                        is required before that date.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The views of the CD Negotiator should be solicited either in person or by
                        cable; <gloss target="#t_ACDA_1">ACDA</gloss> will determine how best to do
                        this.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The PCC will return to the issue at a later date.</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Arms Control Review (NSR–14)</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In addition to the reviews tasked in NSR–14,<note n="2" xml:id="d11fn2"
                            >See <ref target="#d10">Document 10</ref>.</note> a review of U.S.
                        compliance policy is required. Additional details will be developed and
                        promulgated by the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff will circulate a paper on the
                        general Nuclear and Space Talks issues listed in NSR–14. The PCC will deal
                        with this issue on April 19.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>A work program for the review of the Defense and Space position will be
                        promulgated by the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>In addition to the reviews tasked in NSR–14, a review of the initial
                        Soviet proposal in the <gloss target="#t_CFE_1">CFE</gloss> talks is
                        required. This review and the Defense PCC review of the military and
                        political implications of reductions in Europe beyond those in the initial
                        Western <gloss target="#t_CFE_1">CFE</gloss> proposal should both be
                        completed before the <gloss target="#t_NATO_1">NATO</gloss> summit. The PCC
                        will return to the question of the feasibility of such a review in such a
                        brief time period.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>The review of naval arms control will focus on <gloss target="#t_CSBM_1"
                            >CSBM</gloss>s such as deployment restrictions, not on <gloss
                            target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">SLCM</gloss>
                        or numerical limits on naval platforms.</item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="0070" n="43" xml:id="pg_43"/>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Review of the U.S. <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss> Position</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The technical review of the <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> Joint
                        Draft Text will be conducted by the <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                        Backstopping Committee which is reconstituted as a body subordinate to the
                        Arms Control PCC. <gloss target="#t_ACDA_1">ACDA</gloss> will make the
                        necessary arrangements.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>None of the gaps in the U.S. position listed in Tab B<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d11fn3">Attached but not printed. See Tab B, <ref target="#d10"
                                >Document 10</ref>.</note>to NSR–14 <hi rend="italic">require</hi>
                        resolution prior to the resumption of negotiations.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The following items listed in Tab A<note n="4" xml:id="d11fn4">Attached
                            but not printed. See Tab A, <ref target="#d10">Document 10</ref>.</note>
                        to NSR–14 require review at this time. Indicated agencies will provide a
                        brief statement of the issue by <gloss target="#t_COB_1">COB</gloss>
                        Thursday, April 6, 1989. <list>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>The 1600 <gloss target="#t_SNDV_1">SNDV</gloss> limit.
                                (STATE)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Sublimits on <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s. (<gloss
                                    target="#t_ACDA_1">ACDA</gloss>)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Current United States proposals to ban flight testing and
                                modernization of heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s and
                                past contingency proposals to allow heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"
                                    >ICBM</gloss> testing/modernization subject to a formal equal
                                U.S. right to deploy heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s.
                                    (<gloss target="#t_OSD_1">OSD</gloss>)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Allowing the Soviets to retain any heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"
                                    >ICBM</gloss>s. (<gloss target="#t_OSD_1">OSD</gloss>)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Launchweight as a substitute for ballistic missile throwweight.
                                    (<gloss target="#t_ACDA_1">ACDA</gloss>)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Limits on non-deployed ballistic missiles and the current U.S.
                                approach to monitoring such limits. (<gloss target="#t_OSD_1"
                                    >OSD</gloss>)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>The existing U.S. position regarding bomber and air-launched
                                cruise missile limits including all elements listed under item 4 of
                                Tab A of NSR–14. (<gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Staff)</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Restrictions on depressed trajectory ballistic missiles.
                                (STATE)</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>All issues on mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s listed in Tab
                        A to NSR–14 require review. The <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff
                        will frame the issue which will be broken into at least two parts.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>The following do not require review at this time: <list>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Sea-launched cruise missiles.</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Verification issues other than those associated with items listed
                                above.</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Telemetry encryption.</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Backfire.</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Former heavy bomber accountability.</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Whether to permit conversion of <gloss target="#t_SSBN_1"
                                    >SSBN</gloss>s to non-accountable submarines.</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Golf-II class submarines and SS-N-5 missiles.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
